We recommended and Management agreed to –
• direct the Municipal Accountant to –
a) xxx;
b) xxx;
c) xxx; and
d) prepare and maintain PPELC.

We reiterated the following recommendations and Management agreed to direct the – 

Inventory Committee 
conduct complete annual physical count of PPE; 
reconcile the actual count and the existing inventory records, if there is any and submit complete and duly signed RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor not later than the prescribed deadline by the Manual; and
identify the reasons for the differences noted before making any adjustment;


Municipal Accountant 
set up and maintain PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards; and
make the necessary adjusting entry for properties disposed of;

OIC-GSO 
cause the preparation and maintenance of complete and updated Property Cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report; 

take the necessary action to identify all unserviceable government properties; and

prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) so that proper disposal could be undertaken; and 

use the latest prescribed form which is the PAR, and keep the complete file for control and monitoring of the accountability for the issued/ donated PPE; and


Disposal and Appraisal Committee 
inspect unserviceable equipment and property to verify justification for disposal; 
set the final appraised value of all disposable properties;

recommend the disposal to the Local Chief Executive (LCE) for his approval and the manner of disposal; and 

conduct public bidding for the sale of disposable property on an ‘as is, where is basis’ and recommend corresponding award thereof.

We also recommended and Management agreed to follow the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed to - 

set procedural guidelines on the workflow from the receipt, safekeeping and distribution of the procured and donated goods/supplies which will specifically identify the accountable office/officer, including the monitoring tools to be used to facilitate updated records and identification of accountability;

provide additional storage/ cabinets to further secure and arrange the office/ medical supplies in the GSO/MHO; 

require the MDRRMO to request for the immediate repair of the covered court in order to secure the storage of relief goods;

establish sound system of inventory management to 
communicate with the Solid Waste Management Board (SWMB) regarding the proper disposal of expired canned goods due to possible effect of environmental/health hazard regarding the contents and the packaging as well; and 
when the manner of disposal has been decided, request for the presence of the Auditor or her representative during the actual disposal; and

We reiterated our recommendation and Management agreed to – 

instruct the GSO to 

prepare RPCI in the required format and certified correct by the Inventory Committee, attested by the Audit Team’s representative and approved by the Head of the Agency; 
submit RPCI to the Audit Team for audit and validation thereof; and 
guarantee that all food, supplies, drugs and medicines whether purchased by the Municipality or donated by other agencies are recorded by the Municipal Accountant by furnishing delivery receipt and/or AIR;

direct the Municipal Accountant to 
assign a staff who will be responsible in the preparation and maintenance of SLCs and compute the cost of each item using moving average method (except for drugs and medicines with expiration period); and 
use perpetual inventory method instead of direct expense in order to properly account all the unused supplies and/or materials as of a given date;

require the Inventory Custodian/AO to update SCs daily and prepare SSMI to be submitted every week or at least once a month to the Municipal Accountant together with RIS or equivalent document so that issuances will be computed and recorded by the latter; and

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to 

apply for the fidelity bond of Inventory Custodians/Storekeepers who are regular employees of the Municipality; and

furnish the OIC-Municipal Accountant of Monthly Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms with and without Money Value with corresponding RIS as basis on the recording of issuances of accountable forms inventory and to be able to determine the exact quantity and amount of accountable forms on hand as of a given period.

We recommended and Management agreed thru its GFPS, to 
(i) implement all GAD PPAs, client and organization-focused, identified in the GPB; and

(ii) include PPAs to celebrate Women’s Day (March 8th) and observance of International Women’s month (March);

We recommended and Management agreed to –

ensure the (i) preparation of RPCI in the required format as certified correct by the Inventory Committee, attested by the Audit Team’s representative and approved by the Head of the Agency and 

(ii) submission of RPCI to the Audit Team for audit and validation thereof; 


direct the Municipal Accountant to (i) assign a staff who will be responsible in the preparation and maintenance of SLCs and compute the cost of each item using moving average method (except for drugs and medicines with expiration period); and 

require the Inventory Custodian/AO to update SCs daily and prepare SSMI to be submitted every week or at least once a month to the Municipal Accountant together with RIS or equivalent document so that issuances will be computed and recorded by the latter;

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to apply for the fidelity bond of Inventory Custodians/ Storekeepers who are regular employees of the Municipality.

We recommended and Management agreed to - 

reorganize its Inventory Committee and require them to –

conduct complete annual physical count of PPE;
reconcile the actual count and the existing inventory records, if there is any and submit complete and duly signed RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor not later than the prescribed deadline by the Manual;
identify the reasons for the differences noted before making any adjustment;

reorganize its Disposal and Appraisal Committee and instruct them to –

inspect unserviceable equipment and property to verify justification for disposal;
set the final appraised value of all disposable properties;
recommend to the Local Chief Executive (LCE) for approval, the manner of disposal; and
conduct public bidding for the sale of disposable property on an ‘as is, where is basis’ and recommend corresponding award thereof.

We reiterated the following recommendations and Management agreed to – 

direct the OIC-GSO to (i) cause the preparation and maintenance of complete and updated Property Cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report and 

(ii) take the necessary action to identify all unserviceable government properties and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) so that proper disposal could be undertaken; and

direct the Municipal Accountant to (i) set up and maintain PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards; and (ii) make the necessary adjusting entry for properties disposed of.

We recommended and Management agreed to –

require the OIC-Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee and the OIC-Municipal Engineer to work on the completion of the documentary requirements; and address the noted deficiencies and ensure that the required documents for each type of transaction are submitted/attached to the DVs before their processing and payment;

direct the OIC-Municipal Engineer to 

(iii) prepare traffic management plan; 

(iv) require the contractor to strictly implement traffic management; 

(v) prudently undertake detailed engineering activities in order to address issues frequently raise which cause delay in the implementation of the projects; 


(vii) strictly conduct regular inspection monitoring of projects to ensure that projects are implemented on time and approved programs of works are properly complied with; and

We recommended and Management agreed that – 

Municipal Accountant, MDRRMO, OIC-Municipal Engineer and BAC-Chairperson, ensure that all claims against governments funds shall be supported with complete documentation in accordance with Section 4(6) of PD 1445;

MDRRMO and GSO establish sound system of inventory management to prevent government losses, such as but not limited to, guidelines in the distribution of goods near its expiry date (to whom the items will be donated, e.g. prisoners and indigent citizens) and proper storage and handling of goods within the stockroom.

We recommended and Management agreed to –

consider to (i) transfer the electrical connections of market stalls directly to PENELCO in order to save time, funds and effort from reading sub-meters, collecting and remitting/depositing payments, recording of receivables and payments and enforcing actions against defaulting owners of sub-meters; or


(ii)  create/craft clear-cut/written and approved guidelines for the detailed procedures in the over-all operations in the distribution, collection and recording of electric consumption in the NHPMTC and the duties and responsibilities of the assigned personnel/employees, which shall include, (without prejudice to the Management’s decision in incorporating additional controls):

the procedures of electric meter reading and period when to conduct the reading, computation of rates (whether additional percentage be added), deadline of payments and penalties of late payments of electricity consumption; 

the preparation of Summary of Billings and individual billing statement as signed by the preparer and to be submitted to the MTO for the counterchecking of its computation;

the manner of distribution of copies of individual billing statements or statement of accounts, to wit:

Original (white) – Consumer/Owner of sub-meter

Duplicate (pink) – COA (as attachment to OR/AF No. 51)

Triplicate (blue) – Market file

the procedures on how the summary of billings and booklet of bills will be kept intact;

the method of setting up the receivables based on the computed and approved electricity billings of a given month and the maintenance of subsidiary ledger per lessee/owner of sub-meter by the Municipal Accountant’s Office;

the maintenance of index card per lessee/owner of sub-meter by the Market Administrator’s staff for periodic reconciliation with the subsidiary ledger maintained in the Municipal Accountant’s Office;

the remittance of the collector daily and intact to the MTO and/or the corresponding deposit of the latter to the agency depository bank;

the recorded collections as part of income from market operations with sub-account for electricity, for its income identification; and

the salaries/wages of person/s directly involve in NHPMTC and other expenses directly incurred on the electricity connection, disconnection and reconnection
